#Research Flow 

Problem Identification

Identify challenges in streamflow prediction in boreal climate regions.
Highlight limitations of existing models like LSTM in addressing complex dynamics.
Study Area Selection

Select the Upper Humber River Watershed (UHRW), Newfoundland, Canada.
Collect geographic, hydrological, and climate data specific to the region.
Data Collection and Preprocessing

Collect historical data (e.g., streamflow, precipitation, Tmax, Tmin, relative humidity).
Handle missing values, normalize variables, and split data into training, validation, and testing sets.
Model Development

Design the Transformer model architecture:
Encoder-decoder structure for temporal feature extraction.
Attention mechanisms to focus on critical data patterns.
Optimize hyperparameters for improved performance.
Model Training

Train the Transformer model on the preprocessed dataset.
Use advanced techniques like dropout and regularization to prevent overfitting.
Performance Evaluation

Evaluate the model using metrics:
Nash-Sutcliffe Efficiency (NSE)
Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE)
Mean Absolute Error (MAE)
Coefficient of Determination (R²)
Compare performance with LSTM and other models.
Result Interpretation

Analyze the model’s ability to capture seasonal and extreme flow events.
Discuss how the Transformer model adapts to boreal climate dynamics.
Application

Provide insights for water resource management in the UHRW.
Propose strategies for using the model in climate impact studies.
Conclusion and Future Work

Summarize findings and improvements in prediction accuracy.
Recommend future research directions (e.g., integrating more climatic indices, developing hybrid models).
